es. Perhaps it would be wise to investigate how these lifecycle methods interact with the overall test setup, as understanding that could help in ensuring comprehensive test coverage. I'll need to dig deeper into this.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering test frameworks**\\n\\nI’m thinking about the existing scaffold, which probably includes JUnit Jupiter and Vintage but not TestNG. If the tests utilize the `InjectedTest` class, then the compiler might need TestNG. So, I’m considering testing the compilation of a subclass. I plan to use a Gradle classpath and javac to check this out. It seems like a good way to figure out what I need for compiling.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_HwG2Uxo2HQbPaIHxbu13TxAd|fc_0e8402e9090ff7f0016a3ff36e8ea8819481fca3ed1563f3b2", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "cd tests/src/org.sonatype.sisu/sisu-inject-bean/2.4.0\nGVM_TCK_LV=2.4.2 ../../../../../gradlew -q printClasspath >/tmp/cp.txt 2>/tmp/cperr || true\ncat /tmp/cperr | tail -20\n# no printClasspath likely. Build classpath manually via Gradle init script? use dependencies not paths hard.\nTMP=$(mktemp -d); cat >$TMP/T.java <<'EOF'\nimport org.sonatype.guice.bean.containers.InjectedTest;\npublic class T extends InjectedTest { public void configure(com.google.inject.Binder b) {} }\nEOF\n# get paths by find common jars\nJARS=$(find ~/.gradle/caches/modules-2/files-2.1 -path '*/*/*/*.jar' | grep -E '/(sisu-inject-bean/2.4.2|cdi-api/1.0|sisu-guice/3.1.5|org.eclipse.sisu.inject/0.0.0.M5|javax.inject/1|jsr250-api/1.0|junit/4.13.2|hamcrest-core|junit-jupiter-api|junit-platform-commons|opentest4j|apiguardian-api)' | paste -sd: -)\njavac -cp \"$JARS\" $TMP/T.java 2>&1 | sed -n '1,80p'", "timeout": 60}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "oca/gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 907, "output": 1142, "cacheRead": 28160, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 30209, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopR